Description: Please pick up the green block that located on your right and is positioned closest to you.
Strategy: The strategy changed slightly based on where the block was located. In the trials with a certain colored block positioned nearest them, I pointed that out, and attempted to clarify by also mentioning the colored block it was directly adjacent to, in front of or behind. On other trials, I mainly used left-right, and adjacency directionals as well.
Challenging: Some of these were considerably more challenging than I was anticipating. The most challenging trials were definitely the ones with blocks that were positioned further away from the other individual, not entirely on the right, or left, or center, and with analogous chromatic adjacencies. I also found it somewhat challenging to not over-complicate the instructions while still including enough specificity to ensure they would know which block I was referring to.
GeneralComments: Again, some of these were really hard! Also, I tried to catch myself as I realized I was doing it, but I think I may have alternated using the word "tan" and "orange" interchangeably. Hopefully I caught them all. No additional remarks -- everything ran smooth.
ExpWithRobotComments: As far as I can recall, I have never seen a robot in person before. I should probably remedy this posthaste because, truth told, I would really, really love to!

Description: Pick up the blue block that is farthest from you.
Strategy:
Several strategies:
- Pick out ALL the blocks of the same color as the target block
- THEN, identify target block by distance from robot (e.g., closest/farthest blue)
- OR, identify target block by relationship to other blocks of same color (e.g., rightmost blue)
Challenging: Needing multiple steps to identify target block, hoping that robot understood "pick out the three blue blocks that are adjacent to one another" was NOT an action command but instead a preliminary step of defining a subset.

Description: Pick up the green block that has a yellow block below it and a brown block above it.
Strategy: I attempted to use language and directions that would indicate the position on the table in the simplest terms that the robot could understand. My first choice would be if that block was the only one of its color. Second choice would be proximity - closest or furthest from the robot. If those didn't work well, then I went to relative positioning compared to other blocks of either the same color or different colors.
Challenging: I found the task quite challenging. Many of the blocks were not placed in ways where it was easy to come up with descriptors that would feel right. It's difficult to break down a task that seems to simple to a human brain and attempt to get a machine to do what it's being instructed. It's so intuitive for us to follow instructions like those that it's difficult to translate that into a tangible instruction.
GeneralComments: I enjoyed this task. I felt like it was fun and challenging. At the same time, I think the time estimate given for the task seemed long. Also, it would be really beneficial to provide multiple examples of how one might describe stuff to the robot. I felt at times like I was sort of flailing in the wind, and just doing the best I could given limited information. Perhaps that was the intention.

If those didn't work well, then I went to relative positioning compared to other blocks of either the same color or different colors.
Challenging: I found the task quite challenging. Many of the blocks were not placed in ways where it was easy to come up with descriptors that would feel right. It's difficult to break down a task that seems to simple to a human brain and attempt to get a machine to do what it's being instructed. It's so intuitive for us to follow instructions like those that it's difficult to translate that into a tangible instruction.
GeneralComments: I enjoyed this task. I felt like it was fun and challenging. At the same time, I think the time estimate given for the task seemed long. Also, it would be really beneficial to provide multiple examples of how one might describe stuff to the robot. I felt at times like I was sort of flailing in the wind, and just doing the best I could given limited information. Perhaps that was the intention.

Description: Remove the farthest block on your right. Now, choose the block farthest on your right that is closest to you.
Choose the farthest block on your right that also happens to be tied for the farthest block away from you.
There are two blocks directly in the middle of the table in a vertical line. Choose the block directly to the left of those two blocks that's center is between the two center blocks.
Look at the farthest block to your left. Select the block touching it.
Remove the five bottom blocks closest to you. Choose the block that is nearest center of the new lowest 3 blocks.
There are three green blocks touching in a horizontal line near the center of the group. Choose the middle of these three green blocks.
Choose the yellow block farthest from you, in the center.
Choose the only green block on the left side of the table.
Remove the two closest blocks to you, the yellow and blue. Choose the next closest block to you, the orange one farthest to the right.
There are five green blocks arranged like a dice on the left side of the table. Choose the center one.
There are three blocks going vertically in the center of the table, a green and two blues. Choose the blue one closest to you.
Remove the block farthest away from you, which is blue in color. The next farthest block is the blue you should choose.
There are four yellow blocks touching each other on the left side of the table. Choose the second closest to you.
Choose the green block near the center of the table closest to you.
Pick up the green block that is before the two orange blocks.
Strategy: Basically looking at the target block's position, and what's directly around it, if anything.
Challenging: It was mostly easy.  Some individual tasks that had the target block deeper into the other blocks, especially those of its own color, made the explanation a bit longer.
GeneralComments: It was interesting.  Thank you for the opportunity!
ExpWithRobotComments: If the animatronic dinosaurs at the Orlando Islands of Adventure theme park count (and similar things), then yes.

Description: Pick up the green block on the far left, closest to you.
Pick up the yellow block.
Of the two blue blocks just above the orange block closest to you, pick up the one that is further to your right.
Pick up the blue block furthest to your right.
Skip one yellow block above the orange block on your right and pick up the next yellow block above it.
In the clump of five green blocks on your left, pick up the one in the center.
Pick up the orange block closest to you.
Of the two blue blocks closest to each other, pick up the blue block on your left.
Pick up the green block closest to the yellow block that is closest to me.
Pick up the orange block closest to me.
Pick up the green block furthest to your left.
Pick up the orange block closest to you.
Pick up the green block closest to you.
Pick up the yellow block in the middle of three green blocks and one blue block.
Pick up the green block that is closest to you.
Strategy: I was viewing the blocks from the robot's point of view and using directions like "left" or "right" from that point of reference.  I also frequently used words like "furthest from you" or "closest to you", again from the robot's point of reference.
Challenging: The most challenging aspect was differentiating a block that was surrounded by other blocks of the same color.
GeneralComments: Very interesting study and very enjoyable to complete!

Description: Pick up the blue block that's right next to the green block closest to you.
Strategy: Ideally, I could locate a block in a clear, unambiguous way in relation to the other person, e.g. 'the closest [whatever] block to you.' Failing that, I tried to locate the block in relation to other blocks, in such a way that the position was unique, or at least the most probable of several similar possibilities.
Challenging: This actually reminded me of a similar block orienting task I did some time ago for Percy Liang at Stanford! (That is, he's at Stanford, not me. I'm just here doing the HITs.) So I didn't find it too challenging based on that prior experience. But when I had to indicate a block of a certain color when there were numerous such blocks next to each other on the table--that was somewhat tricky. I'd be interested to see whether the instructions would be used to correctly identify the indicated block.
GeneralComments: With the possible exception of the Australian universities, who are operating on a different pay structure, CMU has the best academic HITs on AMT. Thanks for another one.
ExpWithRobotComments: While I've seen them often enough on television, I don't believe I've ever seen one in person.

Description: Pick up the blue block that is third from the left.
Strategy: Divide the table into left and right, near and far. So four quadrants to describe where the chosen block was located.  Also using numbering when necessary to indicate which block i.e. "second yellow block from the left"
Challenging: Somewhat challenging.  It was most difficult when there were multiple blocks of the same color located close together and you had to find a way to descriptively single out one from the others.
GeneralComments: It was fun, was not expecting to enjoy it as much as I did.
